14. Therefore bare reſemblances of evil, are not the object of tenderneſs. Nor is that place 1 Theſ. 5.22. Abſtain from every appearance of evil, ſo to be underſtood. Becauſe if that were the ſenſe, mans life ſhould be a perpetual thraldome; 

                     〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉
                   alſo is as well kind as appearance: and Eſtius ſays well, it is the ſame with that Ch. 4.12. to walk honeſtly towards them without: many good things carry a reſemblance of evil, as diligence in callings of covetuouſneſs; cheerfulneſs of levity; reſervedneſs of anger, lawful recreations of voluptuouſneſs; and commonly all vertues and graces of ſome one extream.
